d and school movements, to the changes in consumer culture, and the project of a modernizing, cosmopolitan middle class society.Tracing the spread of folk dancing, with particular emphases on English Country Dance, International Folk Dance, and Contra, Walkowitz connects the history of folk dance to social and international political influences in America. Through archival research, oral histories, and ethnography of dance communities, City Folk allows dancers and dancing bodies to speak. From the norms of the first half of the century, marked strongly by Anglo-Saxon traditions, to the Cold War nationalism of the post-war era, and finally on to the counterculture movements of the 1970s, City Folk injects the riveting history of folk dance in the middle of the story of modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCountry dancingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDancexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFolk dancingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFolk dancing, English. 4a18th. 4a20th. 4aCountry. 4aDance. 4aEnglish. 4aThis. 4aUS. 4aalso. 4aboth. 4acentury. 4acities. 4acountryside. 4adancer. 4afolk. 4afrom. 4ahimself. 4ahistorian. 4ahistory. 4aimmersed. 4aleap. 4aonly. 4arehearsed. 4arenowned. 4arich. 4aroots. 4asteps. 4astory. 4atold. 4atradition. 4atransatlantic. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814784525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814784525.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE